# Address Indexing Flow Rule

This rule governs address indexing behavior only.

## 1) Canonical flow
1. Trigger indexing for address list (`indexAddressesList`).
2. Poll workflow status per address (`getAddressIndexingJobStatus`).
3. Fetch token pages incrementally while job is active.
4. Ingest fetched tokens into local DB immediately.
5. Stop when terminal status is reached.

## 2) Incremental UX requirement
- On each status poll while non-terminal, fetch and ingest available token pages.
- Users must see partial token results before job completion.

## 3) Terminal state handling
- Stop polling when `status.isDone == true`.
- `completed`: success path.
- `failed` or `canceled`: terminal error path; stop fetching.

## 4) Data integrity constraints
- Preserve per-address workflow mapping (`address <-> workflow_id`).
- Avoid duplicate token ingestion for the same address/page cursor.
- Keep poll loop idempotent and resumable.

## 5) Indexer list-tokens pagination (owners / address playlists)
- Default GraphQL `limit` is `indexerTokensPageSize` (255; schema `Uint8` max). Do not infer “last page” from `items.length < limit` alone; use `nextOffset == null` as the terminal signal.
- **`PersonalTokensSyncService`**: Persists the next request `offset` in `AppStateAddressEntity` (`hasPersonalTokensIndexerNextOffset` / `personalTokensIndexerNextOffset`) so app restarts resume from the indexer cursor. When no cursor is stored, the first offset is the address playlist `itemCount`.
- **`AddressService.syncTokens`** (ingest after indexing): Pages with the same cursor rules inside a single run; list offset is not persisted in app state (workflow-driven ingest; see call sites).
- **Unit coverage**: `test/unit/infra/services/indexer_service_test.dart` (default limit vs explicit `limit`), `address_service_test.dart` (`syncTokens` / `nextOffset`), `personal_tokens_sync_service_test.dart` (cursor chain and persisted offset vs `itemCount`).
